{0 Your first blog}

In this guide, we’ll walk through the process of creating our very
first blog—a fully functional website featuring a custom stylesheet,
templates (using the excellent
{{:https://github.com/tategakibunko/jingoo} Jingoo} templating
engine), articles and pages written in Markdown, an article index
serving as the homepage, and an Atom feed for syndication. Along the
way, we’ll familiarise ourselves with YOCaml’s terminology and key
principles. By the end of this guide, I hope you’ll feel confident
building your own site independently and exploring the documentation
to push customisation as far as you wish!

{1 Foreword}

This course is based on the project setup covered in the
{{!page:introduction} Introduction guide} and uses the concepts
presented in the {{!page:key_concepts} key concepts section}. If you
haven't read it yet, I encourage you to skim through it to ensure you
start with a strong foundation.

Since YOCaml is a framework, there are many ways to achieve the same
result. I don’t claim that the approach presented here is the best or
most efficient—its aim is simply to be the most accessible for
learning YOCaml’s core concepts.

Moreover, to keep things as clear as possible, we won’t dwell too much
on signatures ([mli]). However, do keep in mind that a YOCaml project
is just like any other OCaml project—you are free to structure it
however you like. For a real-world project (beyond this educational
example), it is, of course, advisable to enforce as many constraints
as possible through encapsulation and well-defined interfaces.

